President Joseph R. Biden has declared a major disaster in the Commonwealth of Kentucky due to severe storms, flooding, landslides, and mudslides that occurred from February 27 to March 14, 2021. This declaration allows for federal funding to be provided to affected individuals and communities. Assistance can include grants for temporary housing and home repairs, low-cost loans for property losses, and other programs to aid in recovery. Federal funding is also available for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. Hazard mitigation measures for the entire state are also eligible for cost-sharing funding. John Brogan has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. Residents and business owners in the designated counties can apply for assistance online or by phone. The toll-free telephone numbers will operate from 7:00 a.m. to 9:00 p.m. seven days a week. For further information, the FEMA News Desk can be contacted.